# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: starlark
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:starlark/bazel-software] Similar to build tools like Make, Apache Ant, and Apache Maven, Bazel builds software applications from source code using rules.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] Rules and macros are created in the Starlark language, a dialect of Python.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] There are built-in rules for building software written in Java, Kotlin, Scala, C, C++, Go, Python, Rust, JavaScript, Objective-C, and bash scripts.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] Bazel can produce software application packages suitable for deployment for the Android and iOS operating systems.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] In 2006, Google started the development of a build tool called *Blaze*.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] The motivation was to have a build system that provides both speed and correctness in a large monorepo.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] Bazel was created as an open-source port of Blaze, using its anagram as a name.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] Bazel was first released in March 2015 and entered beta by September 2015.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] Version 1.0 was released in October 2019.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] Bazel has been described as "one of the first openly available cloud build systems".
[src:starlark/bazel-software] It is able to save the history of previously run commands and share the results across multiple users.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] To do so, Bazel requires that the inputs and outputs of build targets are fully specified.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] Bazel is extensible with the Starlark programming language.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] Starlark is an embedded language whose syntax is a subset of the Python syntax.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] However, it doesn't implement many of Python's language features, such as the ability to access the file I/O, in order to avoid extensions that could create side-effects or create build outputs not known to the build system itself.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] Such side-effects could potentially lead to incorrect analysis of the build dependency graph.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] Bazel was designed as a multilanguage build system.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] It is able to build software combining multiple programming languages within the same repository.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] Many commonly used build systems are designed with a preference for a specific programming language.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] Examples of such systems include Ant and Maven for Java, Leiningen for Clojure, sbt for Scala, etc.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] In a repository with multiple languages, combining separate build systems and achieving the build speed and correctness benefits described above can be difficult and problematic.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] Build systems most similar to Bazel are Pants, Buck, Please, and the Brazil build system used internally at Amazon.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] Pants and Buck both aim for similar technical design objectives as Bazel, with Pants being inspired by the Blaze build system used internally at Google.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] Bazel, Pants, Buck, and Please adopted Starlark as a BUILD file parser, respective to its BUILD file syntax.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] Independently developed build systems with similar uses in efficient dependency graph analysis and automated build artifact tracking have been implemented in build systems such as tup.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] Bazel uses a sandbox for compilation steps.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] When Bazel performs a separate compilation, it creates a new directory and fills it with symlinks to the explicit input dependencies for the rule.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] For languages like C or C++, this requires the user to be explicit about the dependencies and it prevents the unexpected inclusion of a similarly named header file from another including directory.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] This sandbox approach leads to issues with common build tools, resulting in a number of workarounds required to correctly compile code under different architectures.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] For example, when performing separate compilation for Mac/Darwin architectures, the compiler writes the input paths into SO and OSO symbols in the Mach-O binary, which can be seen with a command like `nm -a mybinary | grep SO`.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] These paths are needed for finding symbols during debugging.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] As a result, builds in Bazel must correct the compiled objects after the fact, trying to correct path-related issues that arose from the sandbox construction using flags like `-fdebug-prefix-map` and `-oso_prefix`, the latter having become available in Xcode 11.0.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] Similar handling needs to take place in linking phases, rewriting the rpath values in shared object libraries with a command like `install_name_tool`.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] Since Bazel's initial release the logo was a green letter "b" stylized into a stem of a basil plant with two leaves.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] On July 5, 2017, the Bazel Blog announced a new logo, consisting of three green building blocks arranged to shape a heart.
[src:starlark/bazel-software] A few notable users include BMW, Google, SpaceX, Stripe, Tinder, and Uber.
[src:starlark/bazelbuild-starlark] Starlark (formerly known as Skylark) is a language intended for use as a configuration language.
[src:starlark/bazelbuild-starlark] It was designed for the Bazel build system, but may be useful for other projects as well.
[src:starlark/bazelbuild-starlark] This repository is where Starlark features are proposed, discussed, and specified.
[src:starlark/bazelbuild-starlark] It contains information about the language, including the specification.
[src:starlark/bazelbuild-starlark] There are multiple implementations of Starlark.
[src:starlark/bazelbuild-starlark] Like Python, it is a dynamically typed language with high-level data types, first-class functions with lexical scope, and garbage collection.
[src:starlark/bazelbuild-starlark] Independent Starlark threads execute in parallel, so Starlark workloads scale well on parallel machines.
[src:starlark/bazelbuild-starlark] Starlark is a small and simple language with a familiar and highly readable syntax.
[src:starlark/bazelbuild-starlark] You can use it as an expressive notation for structured data, defining functions to eliminate repetition, or you can use it to add scripting capabilities to an existing application.
[src:starlark/bazelbuild-starlark] A Starlark interpreter is typically embedded within a larger application, and the application may define additional domain-specific functions and data types beyond those provided by the core language.
[src:starlark/bazelbuild-starlark] For example, Starlark was originally developed for the Bazel build tool.
[src:starlark/bazelbuild-starlark] Bazel uses Starlark as the notation both for its BUILD files (like Makefiles, these declare the executables, libraries, and tests in a directory) and for its macro language, through which Bazel is extended with custom logic to support new languages and compilers.
[src:starlark/bazelbuild-starlark] If you've ever used Python, this should look very familiar.
[src:starlark/bazelbuild-starlark] In fact, the code above is also a valid Python code.
[src:starlark/bazelbuild-starlark] Still, this short example shows most of the language.
[src:starlark/bazelbuild-starlark] Starlark is indeed a very small language.
[src:starlark/bazelbuild-starlark] The first use-case of the Starlark language is to describe builds: how to compile a C++ or a Scala library, how to build a project and its dependencies, how to run tests.
[src:starlark/bazelbuild-starlark] Describing a build can be surprisingly complex, especially as a codebase mixes multiple languages and targets multiple platforms.
[src:starlark/bazelbuild-starlark] In the future, this repository will contain a complete description of the build API used in Bazel.
[src:starlark/bazelbuild-starlark] The goal is to have a clear specification and precise semantics, in order to interoperate with other systems.
[src:starlark/bazelbuild-starlark] Ideally, other tools will be able to understand the build API and take advantage of it.
[src:starlark/bazelbuild-starlark] Read about the design process if you want to suggest improvements to the specification.
[src:starlark/bazelbuild-starlark] Follow the mailing-list to discuss the evolution of Starlark.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Starlark is a dialect of Python intended for use as a configuration language.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A Starlark interpreter is typically embedded within a larger application, and this application may define additional domain-specific functions and data types beyond those provided by the core language.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] For example, Starlark is embedded within (and was originally developed for) the Bazel build tool.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] This document was derived from the description of the Go implementation of Starlark.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] It was influenced by the Python specification, Copyright 1990–2017, Python Software Foundation, and the Go specification, Copyright 2009–2017, The Go Authors.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Starlark is an untyped dynamic language with high-level data types, first-class functions with lexical scope, and automatic memory management or *garbage collection*.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Starlark is strongly influenced by Python, Starlark syntax is a strict subset of Python and Starlark semantics is almost a subset of that language.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] In particular, its data types and syntax for statements and expressions will be very familiar to any Python programmer.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] However, Starlark is intended not for writing applications but for expressing configuration: its programs are short-lived and have no external side effects and their main result is structured data or side effects on the host application.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] There are no user-defined types, no inheritance, no reflection, no exceptions, no explicit memory management.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The language does not allow recursion or unbounded loops.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Starlark is suitable for use in highly parallel applications.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] An application may invoke the Starlark interpreter concurrently from many threads, without the possibility of a data race, because shared data structures become immutable due to *freezing*.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The language is deterministic and hermetic.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Executing the same file with the same interpreter leads to the same result.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] By default, user code cannot interact with the environment.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Starlark syntax (but not semantics) is a strict subset of Python syntax.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Practically it means, tools working with Python AST can be used to work with Starlark files.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A Starlark program consists of one or more modules.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Each module is defined by a single UTF-8-encoded text file.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Starlark grammar is introduced gradually throughout this document as shown below, and a complete Starlark grammar reference is provided at the end.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The contents of a Starlark file are broken into a sequence of tokens of five kinds: white space, punctuation, keywords, identifiers, and literals.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Each token is formed from the longest sequence of characters that would form a valid token of each kind.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] It is a static error if a floating-point literal denotes a value whose magnitude is too large to be represented as a finite `float` value.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A Starlark string literal denotes a string value.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Literal occurrences of the chosen quotation mark character must be escaped by a preceding backslash.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Within a string literal, the backslash character `\` indicates the start of an *escape sequence*, a notation for expressing things that are impossible or awkward to write directly.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A *literal backslash* is written using the escape `\\`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] An *escaped newline*---that is, a backslash at the end of a line---is ignored, allowing a long string to be split across multiple lines of the source file.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] An *octal escape* encodes a single string element using its octal value.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] It consists of a backslash followed by one, two, or three octal digits [0-7].
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Simiarly, a *hexadecimal escape* encodes a single string element using its hexadecimal value.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] It consists of `\x` followed by two hexadecimal digits [0-9a-fA-F].
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] It is an error if the value of an octal or hexadecimal escape is greater than decimal 127.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A *Unicode escape* denotes the UTF-K encoding of a single, valid Unicode code point, where K is the implementation-defined number of bits in each string element (see strings).
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The `\uXXXX` form, with exactly four hexadecimal digits, denotes a 16-bit code point, and the `\UXXXXXXXX`, with exactly eight digits, denotes a 32-bit code point.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] It is an error if the value lies in the surrogate range (U+D800 to U+DFFF) or is greater than U+10FFFF.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Although string values may be capable of representing any sequence of elements, string *literals* can denote only sequences of UTF-K code units that are valid encodings of text.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] (Any literal syntax capable of representing arbitrary element sequences would inherently be non-portable across implementations.) Consequently, when the `repr` function is applied to a string containing an invalid encoding, its result is not a valid string literal.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] An ordinary string literal may not contain an unescaped newline, but a *multiline string literal* may spread over multiple source lines.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] It is denoted using three quotation marks at start and end.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Within it, unescaped newlines and quotation marks (or even pairs of quotation marks) have their literal meaning, but three quotation marks end the literal.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] This makes it easy to quote large blocks of text with few escapes.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Regardless of the platform's convention for text line endings---for example, a linefeed (\n) on UNIX, or a carriage return followed by a linefeed (\r\n) on Microsoft Windows---an unescaped line ending in a multiline string literal always denotes a line feed (\n).
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Starlark also supports *raw string literals*, which look like an ordinary single- or double-quotation preceded by `r`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Within a raw string literal, there is no special processing of backslash escapes, other than an escaped quotation mark (which denotes a literal quotation mark), or an escaped newline (which denotes a backslash followed by a newline).
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] It is an error for a backslash to appear within a string literal other than as part of one of the escapes described above.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A Starlark bytes literal denotes a bytes value, and looks like a string literal, in any of its various forms (single-quoted, double-quoted, triple-quoted, raw) preceded by the letter `b`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A raw bytes literal may be indicated by either a `br` or `rb` prefix.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Non-escaped text within a bytes literal denotes the UTF-8 encoding of that text.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Any valid string literal that, with a `b` prefix, is also a valid bytes literal is equivalent in the sense that the bytes value is the UTF-8 encoding of the string value.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Starlark is space-sensitive language, and indentation is used to denote a block of statements.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Unlike Python, indentation can only be composed of space characters (U+0020), not tabs.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Some functions, such as the `range` function, return instances of special-purpose types that don't appear in this list.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Additional data types may be defined by the host application into which the interpreter is embedded, and those data types may participate in basic operations of the language such as arithmetic, comparison, indexing, and function calls.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Some operations, like `bool(x)` or `str(x)`, can be applied to any Starlark value, while others, like integer indexing `a[i]`, apply only to certain types.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The *value concepts* section explains the groupings of types by the operators they support.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] `None` is a distinguished value used to indicate the absence of any other value.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] For example, the result of a call to a function that contains no return statement is `None`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] There are two Boolean values, `True` and `False`, representing the truth or falsehood of a predicate.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Boolean values are typically used as conditions in `if` statements, although any Starlark value may be used in this way.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] All other core language values are considered true.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Application-defined types determine their own truth value.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Any value may be explicitly converted to a Boolean using the built-in `bool` function.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] True and False may be converted to the values 1 and 0 using the `int` function, but Booleans are not numbers.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Testing a non-Boolean value for equality to a Boolean using `==` returns `False`, regardless of whether they have the same truth value.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The Starlark integer type represents integers.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Integers may be positive or negative, and arbitrarily large.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Integers are totally ordered; comparisons follow mathematical tradition.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The `+` and `-` operators perform addition and subtraction, respectively.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The `*` operator performs multiplication.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The `//` and `%` operations on integers compute floored division and remainder of floored division, respectively.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] If the signs of the operands differ, the sign of the remainder `x % y` matches that of the divisor, `y`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The `/` operator implements floating-point division, and yields a `float` result even when its operands are both of type `int`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Integers, including negative values, may be interpreted as bit vectors.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Negative values use two's complement representation.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The `|`, `&`, and `^` operators implement bitwise OR, AND, and XOR, respectively.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The unary `~` operator yields the bitwise inversion of its integer argument.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The `<<` and `>>` operators shift the first argument to the left or right by the number of bits given by the second argument.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Any bool, number, or string may be interpreted as an integer by using the `int` built-in function.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] An integer used in a Boolean context is considered true if it is non-zero.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The Starlark floating-point data type represents an IEEE 754 double-precision floating-point number.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Arithmetic on floats using the `+`, `-`, `*`, `/`, `//`, and `%` operators follows the IEEE 754 standard.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] However, computing the division or remainder of division by zero is a dynamic error.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] An arithmetic operation applied to a mixture of `float` and `int` operands works as if the `int` operand were first converted to a `float`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The implicit conversion fails if the `int` value is too large to be represented as a `float`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] There are two floating-point division operators: `x / y` yields the floating-point quotient of `x` and `y`, whereas `x // y` yields `floor(x / y)`, that is, the largest representable integer value not greater than `x / y`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Although the resulting number is integral, it is represented as a `float` if either operand is a `float`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The `%` operation computes the remainder of floored division.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] As with the corresponding operation on integers, if the signs of the operands differ, the sign of the remainder `x % y` matches that of the divisor, `y`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] All float values are ordered, so they may be compared using operators such as `==` and `<`, and sorted using `sorted`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] IEEE 754 defines two zero values, +0.0 and -0.0.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] IEEE 754 defines two infinite float values `+Inf` and `-Inf`, which represent numbers greater/less than all finite float values.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] IEEE 754 defines many "not a number" (NaN) values.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] They are non-finite, and represent the results of dubious operations such as `Inf / Inf`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] All NaN values compare equal to each other, but greater than any non-NaN `float` value.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A comparison operation may be applied to a mixture of int and float values.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The result of such comparisons is mathematically exact, even if neither operand can be exactly represented by the type of the other.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Any bool, number, or string may be interpreted as a floating-point number by using the `float` built-in function.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A float used in a Boolean context is considered true if it is non-zero (not equal to 0.0 or -0.0).
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A string is an immutable array of elements that encode Unicode text.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] For reasons of efficiency and interoperability with the host language, the number of bits in each string element, which we call K, is specified to be either 8 or 16, depending on the implementation.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] For example, in the Go and Rust implementations, each string element is an 8-bit value (a byte) and Unicode text is encoded as UTF-8, whereas in the Java implementation, string elements are 16-bit values (Java `char`s) and Unicode text is encoded as UTF-16.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] An implementation may permit strings to hold arbitrary values of the element type, including sequences that do not encode valid Unicode text; or, it may disallow invalid sequences, and operations that would form them.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The built-in `len` function returns the number of elements in a string.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Strings may be concatenated with the `+` operator.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The result of both operations is another string (with length 1, in the case of indexing).
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Strings are hashable, and thus may be used as keys in a dictionary.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Strings are totally ordered lexicographically, so strings may be compared using operators such as `==` and `<`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Strings are *not* iterable, so they cannot be used as the operand of a `for` loop or of methods that expect iterables (such as the `list()` constructor).
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] One must instead explicitly call a method of a string value to obtain an iterable view of its elements.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Because strings are not iterable, they are not considered to be subtypes of `Collection` or `Sequence`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Any value may formatted as a string using the `str` or `repr` built-in functions, the `str % tuple` operator, or the `str.format` method.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A string used in a Boolean context is considered true if it is non-empty.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A *bytes* is an immutable array of integers in the range 0-255.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Unlike a string, which is intended for text, a bytes may represent binary data, such as the contents of an arbitrary file, without loss.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The built-in `len` function returns the number of elements (bytes) in a `bytes`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Two bytes values may be concatenated with the `+` operator.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The result of indexing is the value of the byte at the given position, as an integer.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The result of slicing is another bytes object.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The comparison `x in b`, where `b` is a bytes value and `x` is an integer in the range [0, 255], tests whether `x`'s value is an element of `b`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] If `x` is instead another bytes value, the comparison tests whether `x` is contained as a consecutive subsequence of `b` (analogous to substrings of a string).
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] It is an error if `x` is an out-of-range integer, or any other type of value.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Like strings, bytes values are hashable, totally ordered, and considered True if they are non-empty.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] They are not iterable, and not a subtype of `Collection` nor `Sequence`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The number of elements may be retrieved with the built-in `len()` function.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Lists can be indexed to retrieve a single element, and sliced to produce a new list.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Lists can be iterated over by `for` loops.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Lists can also be constructed from any iterable by using the built-in `list` function.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] List elements may be added using the `append` or `extend` methods, removed using the `remove` method, or reordered by assignments such as `list[i] = list[j]`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The concatenation operation `x + y` yields a new list containing all the elements of the two lists x and y.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] For most types, `x += y` is equivalent to `x = x + y`, except that it evaluates `x` only once, that is, it allocates a new list to hold the concatenation of `x` and `y`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] However, if `x` refers to a list, the statement does not allocate a new list but instead mutates the original list in place, similar to `x.extend(y)`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Lists are not hashable, so may not be used in the keys of a dictionary.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A list used in a Boolean context is considered true if it is non-empty.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A *list comprehension* creates a new list whose elements are the result of some expression applied to each element of another sequence.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A tuple is an immutable sequence of values.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Like lists, tuple is a subtype of `Sequence`, and supports the same `len()`, indexing, slicing, and iteration operations.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A slice of a tuple returns another tuple.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Observe that for the 1-tuple, the trailing comma is necessary to distinguish it from the parenthesized expression `(1)`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Tuples can be constructed from any iterable by using the built-in `tuple` function.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Unlike lists, tuples cannot be modified.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] However, the mutable elements of a tuple may be modified.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Tuples are hashable if their elements are hashable, in which case they may be used as keys of a dictionary.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Tuples may be concatenated using the `+` operator.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Note that it is not legal to directly concatenate a tuple with a list.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A tuple used in a Boolean context is considered true if it is non-empty.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A dictionary is a mutable mapping from keys to values.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Dictionaries provide constant-time operations to insert an element, to look up the value for a key, or to remove an element.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Dictionaries are implemented using hash tables, so keys must be hashable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Hashable values include `None`, Booleans, numbers, strings, and bytes, and tuples composed from hashable values.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Most mutable values, such as lists, dictionaries, and sets, are not hashable, unless they are frozen.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Attempting to use a non-hashable value as a key in a dictionary results in a dynamic error.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The expression `d[k]`, where `d` is a dictionary and `k` is a key, retrieves the value associated with the key.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A dictionary can also be constructed using a dictionary comprehension, which evaluates a pair of expressions, the *key* and the *value*, for every element of another iterable such as a list.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Dictionaries are a subtype of `Mapping`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Iteration yields the keys in the order that they were inserted; updating the value associated with an existing key does not affect the iteration order.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Like all mutable values in Starlark, a dictionary can be frozen, and once frozen, all subsequent operations that attempt to update it will fail.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A dictionary used in a Boolean context is considered true if it is non-empty.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The binary `|` operation may be applied to two dictionaries.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] It yields a new dictionary whose set of keys is the union of the sets of keys of the two operands.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The corresponding values are taken from the operands, where the value taken from the right operand takes precedence if both contain a given key.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Iterating over the keys in the resulting dictionary first yields all keys in the left operand in insertion order, then all keys in the right operand that were not present in the left operand, again in insertion order.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] There is also an augmented assignment version of the `|` operation.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] For two dictionaries `d1` and `d2`, the expression `d1 |= d2` behaves similar to `d1 = d1 | d2`, but mutates `d1` in-place rather than assigning a new dictionary to it.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Dictionaries may be compared for equality using `==` and `!=`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Two dictionaries compare equal if they contain the same number of items and each key/value item (k, v) found in one dictionary is also present in the other.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Dictionaries are not ordered; it is an error to compare two dictionaries with `<`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A set is a mutable collection of unique values - the set's *elements*.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Sets provide constant-time operations to insert, remove, or check for the presence of a value.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Sets are implemented using a hash table, and therefore, just like keys of a dictionary, elements of a set must be hashable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A value may be used as an element of a set if and only if it may be used as a key of a dictionary.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Sets may be constructed using the set() built-in function, which returns a set containing all the elements of its optional argument, which must be an iterable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Calling `set()` without an argument constructs an empty set.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Its size can be retrieved using the len() built-in function, and the order of iteration is the order in which elements were inserted.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A set used in Boolean context is true if and only if it is non-empty.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Sets may be compared for equality or inequality using `==` and `!=`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A set `s` is equal to `t` if and only if `t` is a set containing the same elements; iteration order is not significant.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] In particular, a set is *not* equal to the list of its elements.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Sets are not ordered with respect to other sets, and an attempt to compare two sets using `<`, `<=`, `>`, `>=`, or to sort a sequence of sets, will fail.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The `|` operation on two sets returns the union of the two sets: a set containing the elements found in either one or both of the original sets.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The `&` operation on two sets returns the intersection of the two sets: a set containing only the elements found in both of the original sets.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The `-` operation on two sets returns the difference of the two sets: a set containing the elements found in the left-hand side set but not the right-hand side set.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The `^` operation on two sets returns the symmetric difference of the two sets: a set containing the elements found in exactly one of the two original sets, but not in both.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] In each of the above operations, the elements of the resulting set retain their order from the two operand sets, with all elements that were drawn from the left-hand side ordered before any element that was only present in the right-hand side.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The corresponding augmented assignments, `|=`, `&=`, `-=`, and `^=`, modify the left-hand set in place.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Like all mutable values in Starlark, a set can be frozen, and once frozen, all subsequent operations that attempt to update it will fail.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A function value represents a function defined in Starlark.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A function value used in a Boolean context is always considered true.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Functions defined by a `def` statement are named; functions defined by a `lambda` expression are anonymous.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Function definitions may be nested, and an inner function may refer to a local variable of an outer function.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Starlark has no equivalent of Python's `nonlocal` keyword, and thus no way for an inner function cannot assign to a local variable of an outer function.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] However, the inner function may mutate the value of such variables until they become frozen.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A function definition defines zero or more named parameters.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Starlark has a rich mechanism for passing arguments to functions.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The example below shows a definition and call of a function of two required parameters, `x` and `y`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A call may provide arguments to function parameters either by position, as in the example above, or by name, as in first two calls below, or by a mixture of the two forms, as in the third call below.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] All the positional arguments must precede all the named arguments.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Named arguments may improve clarity, especially in functions of several parameters.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] If a function parameter's default value is a mutable expression, modifications to the value during one call may be observed by subsequent calls.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Beware of this when using lists or dicts as default values.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] If the function becomes frozen, its parameters' default values become frozen too.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] It is a static error if any two parameters of a function have the same name.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Once the parameters have been successfully bound to the arguments supplied by the call, the sequence of statements that comprise the function body is executed.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] It is a static error if a function call has two named arguments of the same name, such as `f(x=1, x=2)`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A call that provides a `**kwargs` argument may yet have two values for the same name, such as `f(x=1, **dict(x=2))`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Function arguments are evaluated in the order they appear in the call.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Unlike Python, Starlark does not allow more than one `*args` argument in a call, and if a `*args` argument is present it must appear after all positional and named arguments.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] In particular, even though keyword-only arguments (see below) are declared after `*args` in a function's definition, they nevertheless must appear before `*args` in a call to the function.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A function call completes normally after the execution of either a `return` statement, or of the last statement in the function body.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The result of the function call is the value of the return statement's operand, or `None` if the return statement had no operand or if the function completeted without executing a return statement.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] It is a dynamic error for a function to call itself or another function value with the same declaration.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] This rule, combined with the invariant that all loops are iterations over finite sequences, implies that Starlark programs are not Turing-complete.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] However, an implementation may allow clients to disable this check, allowing unbounded recursion.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A built-in function is a function or method implemented by the interpreter or the application into which the interpreter is embedded.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Its type is `"builtin_function_or_method"`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] A built-in function value used in a Boolean context is always considered true.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Many built-in functions are predeclared in the environment; see Name Resolution.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Some built-in functions such as `len` are *universal*, that is, available to all Starlark programs.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] The host application may predeclare additional built-in functions in the environment of a specific module.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p01] Except where noted, built-in functions accept only positional arguments.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] After a Starlark file is parsed, but before its execution begins, the Starlark interpreter checks statically that the program is well formed.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] For example, `break` and `continue` statements may appear only within a `for` statement; `if`, `for`, and `return` statements may appear only within a function; and `load` statements may appear only outside any function.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Four Starlark constructs bind names, as illustrated in the example below: `load` statements (`a` and `b`), `def` statements (`c`), function parameters (`d`), and assignments (`e`, `h`, including the augmented assignment `e += h`).
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Variables may be assigned or re-assigned explicitly (`e`, `h`), or implicitly, as in a `for` statement (`f`) or comprehension `for` clause (`g`, `i`).
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The environment of a Starlark program is structured as a tree of *lexical blocks*, each of which may contain name bindings.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The tree of blocks is parallel to the syntax tree.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] At the root of the tree is the *predeclared* block, which binds several names implicitly.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The set of predeclared names includes the universal constant values `None`, `True`, and `False`, and various built-in functions such as `len` and `list`; these functions are immutable and stateless.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] An application may pre-declare additional names to provide domain-specific functions to that file, for example.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] These additional functions may have side effects on the application.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Starlark programs cannot change the set of predeclared bindings or assign new values to them (but they can be redefined in a smaller block).
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Nested beneath the predeclared block is the *module* block, which contains the bindings of the current module.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Bindings in the module block (such as `a`, `b`, `c`, and `h` in the example) are called *global* and may be visible to other modules.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The module block is empty at the start of the file and is populated by top-level binding statements, but an application may pre-bind one or more global names, to provide domain-specific functions to that file, for example.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Nested beneath the module block is the *file* block, which contains bindings local to the current file.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Names in this block (such as `a` and `b` in the example) are bound only by `load` statements.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The sets of names bound in the file block and in the module block do not overlap: it is an error for a load statement to bind the name of a global, or for a top-level statement to bind a name bound by a load statement.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] A file block contains a *function* block for each top-level function, and a *comprehension* block for each top-level comprehension.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Bindings in either of these kinds of block, and in the file block itself, are called *local*.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] (In the example, the bindings for `e`, `f`, `g`, and `i` are all local.) Additional functions and comprehensions, and their blocks, may be nested in any order, to any depth.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] If name is bound anywhere within a block, all uses of the name within the block are treated as references to that binding, even if the use appears before the binding.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] This is true even at the top level, unlike Python.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The binding of `y` on the last line of the example below makes `y` local to the function `hello`, so the use of `y` in the print statement also refers to the local `y`, even though it appears earlier.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The same is also true for nested loops in comprehensions.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] In the (unnatural) examples below, the scope of the variables `x`, `y`, and `z` is the entire compehension block, except the operand of the first loop (`[]` or `[1]`), which is resolved in the enclosing environment.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The second loop may thus refer to variables defined by the third (`z`), even though such references would fail if actually executed.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] It is a static error to refer to a name that has no binding at all.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] If a name was pre-bound by the application, the Starlark program may explicitly bind it, but only once.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] An augmented assignment statement such as `x += 1` is considered a binding of `x`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] It is therefore a static error to use it on a global variable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] A name appearing after a dot, such as `split` in `get_filename().split('/')`, is not resolved statically.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The dot expression `.split` is a dynamic operation on the value returned by `get_filename()`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Starlark has over a dozen core data types.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] An application that embeds the Starlark intepreter may define additional types that behave like Starlark values.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Starlark is an imperative language: programs consist of sequences of statements executed for their side effects.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] For example, an assignment statement updates the value held by a variable, and calls to some built-in functions such as `print` change the state of the application that embeds the interpreter.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Values of some data types, such as `NoneType`, `bool`, `int`, `float`, `string`, and `bytes`, are *immutable*; they can never change.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Immutable values have no notion of *identity*: it is impossible for a Starlark program to tell whether two integers, for instance, are represented by the same object; it can tell only whether they are equal.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Values of other data types, such as `list` and `dict`, are *mutable*: they may be modified by a statement such as `a[i] = 0` or `items.clear()`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Although `tuple` and `function` values are not directly mutable, they may refer to mutable values indirectly, so for this reason we consider them mutable too.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Starlark values of these types are actually *references* to variables.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Copying a reference to a variable, using an assignment statement for instance, creates an *alias* for the variable, and the effects of operations applied to the variable through one alias are visible through all others.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Starlark uses *call-by-value* parameter passing: in a function call, argument values are assigned to function parameters as if by assignment statements.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] As in all imperative languages, understanding *aliasing*, the relationship between reference values and the variables to which they refer, is crucial to writing correct programs.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Starlark has a feature unusual among imperative programming languages: a mutable value may be *frozen* so that all subsequent attempts to mutate it fail with a dynamic error; the value, and all other values reachable from it, become *immutable*.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Immediately after execution of a Starlark module, all values in its top-level environment are frozen.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Because all the global variables of an initialized Starlark module are immutable, the module may be published to and used by other threads in a parallel program without the need for locks.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] For example, the Bazel build system loads and executes BUILD and .bzl files in parallel, and two modules being executed concurrently may freely access variables or call functions from a third without the possibility of a race condition.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The `dict` data type is implemented using hash tables, so only *hashable* values are suitable as keys of a `dict`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Attempting to use a non-hashable value as the key in a dictionary results in a dynamic error.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The hash of a value is an unspecified integer chosen so that two equal values have the same hash, in other words, `x == y => hash(x) == hash(y)`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] A hashable value has the same hash throughout its lifetime.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Values of the types `NoneType`, `bool`, `int`, `float`, `string`, and `bytes`, which are all immutable, are hashable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Values of mutable types such as `list` and `dict` are not hashable, unless they have become immutable due to *freezing*.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] A `tuple` value is hashable only if all its elements are hashable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Values of the types `function` and `builtin_function_or_method` are also hashable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Although functions are not necessarily immutable, as they may be closures that refer to mutable variables, instances of these types are compared by reference identity (see Comparisons), so their hash values are derived from their identity.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Starlark defines several abstract data types.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Although these are not directly referenced by name in Starlark programs, they are useful concepts for understanding what operations a type supports and for documenting what types a function expects.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Applications may define additional data structures that may or may not have a particular abstract data type.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] If it does have the type, it must support all of its required operations, but the converse is not necessarily true.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] It is a dynamic error to mutate a collection such as a list, set, or dictionary while iterating over it.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] This helps avoid a common source of errors and implementation pitfalls.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] In Python, the result is `[5, 12, 8]` -- the `12` is missed due to the implicit iterator's internal integer indexing.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] But in Starlark, an error is raised at the attempt to mutate `a` inside the loop.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The same code would succeed with the correct result in both languages if the loop were rewritten as `for x in list(a)`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Unlike Python 3, the result of certain methods like `enumerate()` or `zip()` is a new list rather than an iterator object.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Loops over such lists will not prevent modifying the original list.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Many Starlark operators and functions require an index operand `i`, such as `a[i]` or `list.insert(i, x)`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Others require two indices `i` and `j` that indicate the start and end of a subsequence, such as `a[i:j]`, `list.index(x, i, j)`, or `string.find(x, i, j)`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] All such operations follow similar conventions, described here.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The first element of a string or list has index 0, the next 1, and so on.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The last element of a sequence of length `n` has index `n-1`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] For subsequence operations that require two indices, the first is *inclusive* and the second *exclusive*.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Thus `a[i:j]` indicates the sequence starting with element `i` up to but not including element `j`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The length of this subsequence is `j-i`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] This convention is known as *half-open indexing*.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Either or both of the index operands may be omitted.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] It is permissible to supply a negative integer to an indexing operation.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The effective index is computed from the supplied value by the following two-step procedure.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] First, if the value is negative, the length of the sequence is added to it.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Second, for subsequence operations, if the value is still negative, it is replaced by zero, or if it is greater than the length `n` of the sequence, it is replaced by `n`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] In effect, the index is "truncated" to the nearest value in the range `[0:n]`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] An expression specifies the computation of a value.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The Starlark grammar defines several categories of expression.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] An *operand* is an expression consisting of a single token (such as an identifier or a literal), or a bracketed expression.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] An operand may be followed by any number of dot, call, or slice suffixes, to form a *primary* expression.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] In some places in the Starlark grammar where an expression is expected, it is legal to provide a comma-separated list of expressions denoting a tuple.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The grammar uses `Expressions` where a multiple-component expression is allowed, and `Expression` where it accepts an expression of only a single component.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] An identifier is a name that identifies a value.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Lookup of locals and globals may fail if not yet defined.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Evaluation of an int, float, string, or bytes literal yields the value of that literal.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] See [Literals](#lexical elements) for details.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] A single expression enclosed in parentheses yields the result of that expression.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Explicit parentheses may be used for clarity, or to override the default association of subexpressions.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] If the parentheses are empty, or contain a single expression followed by a comma, or contain two or more expressions, the expression yields a tuple.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] In some contexts, such as a `return` or assignment statement or the operand of a `for` statement, a tuple may be expressed without parentheses.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] A dictionary expression is a comma-separated list of colon-separated key/value expression pairs, enclosed in curly brackets, and it yields a new dictionary object.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] An optional comma may follow the final pair.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The key and value expressions are evaluated in left-to-right order.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Evaluation fails if the same key is used multiple times.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Only hashable values may be used as the keys of a dictionary.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] A list expression is a comma-separated list of element expressions, enclosed in square brackets, and it yields a new list object.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] An optional comma may follow the last element expression.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Element expressions are evaluated in left-to-right order.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] There are four unary operators, all appearing before their operand: `+`, `-`, `~`, and `not`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The `+` and `-` operators may be applied to any number: `+` yields the operand unchanged, and `-` yields its negation.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The `+` operator is never necessary in a correct program but may serve as an assertion that its operand is a number, or as documentation.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The `not` operator returns the negation of the truth value of its operand.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The `~` operator yields the bitwise inversion of its integer argument.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The bitwise inversion of x is defined as -(x+1).
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Comparison operators, `in`, and `not in` are non-associative, so the parser will not accept `0 <= i < n`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] All other binary operators of equal precedence associate to the left.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The `or` and `and` operators yield, respectively, the logical disjunction and conjunction of their arguments, which need not be Booleans.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The expression `x or y` yields the value of `x` if its truth value is `True`, or the value of `y` otherwise.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Similarly, `x and y` yields the value of `x` if its truth value is `False`, or the value of `y` otherwise.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The `==` operator reports whether its operands are equal; the `!=` operator is its negation.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The operators `<`, `>`, `<=`, and `>=` perform an ordered comparison of their operands.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] It is an error to apply these operators to operands of unequal type, unless one of the operands is an `int` and the other is a `float`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Comparison of floating-point values follows the IEEE 754 standard for finite values (including -0.0) and for positive and negative infinity, but not for `NaN` values, for which the standard behavior would break several mathematical identities.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Applications may define additional types that support ordered comparison.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The application-defined comparison relation must be a strict weak ordering.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The remaining built-in types support only equality comparisons.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Values of type `dict` compare equal if their elements compare equal, and values of type `function` are equal only to themselves.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The operands of the arithmetic operators `+`, `-`, `*`, `//`, and `%`, must both be numbers (`int` or `float`) but need not have the same type.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The type of the result has type `int` only if both operands have that type.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The result of floating-point division `/` always has type `float`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The `&` operator requires two operands of type `int`, and yields the bitwise intersection (AND) of its operands.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The `|` operator likewise computes bitwise union, and the `^` operator bitwise XOR (exclusive OR).
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The `<<` and `>>` operators require two operands of type `int`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] They shift the first operand to the left or right by the number of bits given by the second operand.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Right shifts are arithmetic, not logical: they fill the vacated bits with copies of the sign bit.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] It is a dynamic error if the second operand is negative.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The `+` operator may be applied to non-numeric operands of the same type, such as two lists, two tuples, two strings, or two bytes, in which case it computes the concatenation of the two operands and yields a new value of the same type.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The `*` operator may be applied to an integer *n* and a value of type `string`, `bytes`, `list`, or `tuple`, in which case it yields a new value of the same sequence type consisting of *n* repetitions of the original sequence.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The order of the operands is immaterial.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Negative values of *n* behave like zero.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Applications may define additional types that support any subset of these operators.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The `in` operator reports whether its first operand is a member of its second operand, which must be a list, tuple, dict, set, string, or bytes.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The meaning of membership varies by the type of the second operand: the members of a list or tuple are its elements; the members of a dict are its keys; the members of a string or bytes are all its substrings.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Additionally, the members of a bytes include the int values of its (byte) elements.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The expression `format % args` performs *string interpolation*, a simple form of template expansion.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The `format` string is interpreted as a sequence of literal portions and *conversions*.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Each conversion, which starts with a `%` character, is replaced by its corresponding value from `args`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The characters following `%` in each conversion determine which argument it uses and how to convert it to a string.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Each `%` character marks the start of a conversion specifier, unless it is immediately followed by another `%`, in which cases both characters together denote a single literal percent sign.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The conversion's operand is the next element of `args`, which must be a tuple with exactly one component per conversion, unless the format string contains only a single conversion, in which case `args` itself is its operand.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Starlark does not support the flag, width, and padding specifiers supported by Python's `%` and other variants of C's `printf`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The compact form `%g` is also used by `str(float)`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] It is an error if the argument does not have the type required by the conversion specifier, except that ints may converted to floats and floats may truncated to ints.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] A Boolean argument is not considered a number.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] A conditional expression has the form `a if cond else b`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] It first evaluates the condition `cond`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] If it's true, it evaluates `a` and yields its value; otherwise it yields the value of `b`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] During parsing, the `if` operator, considered as a postfix operator on the "true" expression, has higher precedence than `else` (a prefix operator on the "false" expression), which in turn has higher precedence than the `lambda` prefix operator.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] A comprehension constructs new list or dictionary value by looping over one or more iterables and evaluating a *body* expression that produces successive elements of the result.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] A list comprehension consists of a single expression followed by one or more *clauses*, the first of which must be a `for` clause.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Each `for` clause resembles a `for` statement, and specifies an iterable operand and a set of variables to be assigned by successive values of the iterable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] An `if` cause resembles an `if` statement, and specifies a condition that must be met for the body expression to be evaluated.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] A sequence of `for` and `if` clauses acts like a nested sequence of `for` and `if` statements.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] A dict comprehension resembles a list comprehension, but its body is a pair of expressions, `key: value`, separated by a colon, and its result is a dictionary containing the key/value pairs for which the body expression was evaluated.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Evaluation fails if the value of any key is unhashable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] A value `f` of type `function` may be called using the expression `f(...)`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Applications may define additional types whose values may be called in the same way.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] A method call such as `filename.endswith(".sky")` is the composition of two operations, `m = filename.endswith` and `m(".sky")`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The first, a dot operation, yields a *bound method*, a function value that pairs a receiver value (the `filename` string) with a choice of method (string·endswith).
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Only built-in or application-defined types may have methods.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] See Functions for an explanation of function parameter passing.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] A dot expression `x.f` selects the attribute `f` (a field or method) of the value `x`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Fields are possessed by none of the main Starlark data types, but some application-defined types have them.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Methods belong to the built-in types `string`, `list`, `dict`, and `set` and to many application-defined types.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] A dot expression fails if the value does not have an attribute of the specified name.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Use the built-in function `hasattr(x, "f")` to ascertain whether a value has a specific attribute, or `dir(x)` to enumerate all its attributes.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The `getattr(x, "f")` function can be used to select an attribute when the name `"f"` is not known statically.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] But when not called immediately, the dot expression evaluates to a *bound method*, that is, a method coupled to a specific receiver value.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] A subscript expression `a[x]` retrieves a value identified by `x` from the value `a`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] There are two main cases: indexing a sequence, and retrieving values of a mapping.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] When `a` is a `Sequence` (such as a `list` or `tuple`), or another indexable object like `string` or `bytes`, the expression `a[i]` yields the `i`th element of `a`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Here, `i` must be an `int` value in the range `-n` ≤ `i` < `n`, where `n` is `len(a)`; any other index results in an error.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] A valid negative index `i` behaves like the non-negative index `n+i`, allowing for convenient indexing relative to the end of the sequence.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] For a subscript expression `m[k]`, where the value of `m` is a `Mapping` (most commonly a `dict`) or any other mapping-like object, the expression retrieves the value that `m` associates with `k`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] It is an error if `m` contains no such key `k`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] It is a dynamic error to attempt to update an element of an immutable type, such as a tuple or string, or a frozen value of a mutable type.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Starlark does not have a `del` statement like Python.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Deleting the value associated with an index or key requires calling a method on the containing object.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The slice expression acts as a sort of indexing subscript expression that retrieves a range of elements rather than a single element.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] It applies to types that can be indexed with an integer as above, such as `Sequence`s, `string`, and `bytes`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] A slice expression `a[start:stop:stride]` yields a copy of `a` containing exactly the values whose indices are in the specified range.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Conceptually, the range begins at `start`, progresses in increments of `stride`, and ends before reaching `stop`, without ever going out-of-bounds.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Each of the `start`, `stop`, and `stride` operands may be `None` or omitted entirely; otherwise, they must evaluate to integers.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] If `stride` is omitted then the second colon may optionally also be omitted.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] If `stride` is omitted its value defaults to 1.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] It is an error to specify a `stride` of 0.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The effective start and stop indices are computed from the three operands as follows.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Unlike Python, Starlark does not allow a slice expression to be the target of an assignment, although it may appear as a subexpression in the target.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Slicing a tuple, string, or bytes may be more efficient than slicing a list because tuple, string, and bytes values are immutable, so the result of the operation can share the underlying representation of the original operand (when the stride is 1).
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] By contrast, slicing a list requires the creation of a new list and copying of the necessary elements.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] A `lambda` expression yields a new function value.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] Syntactically, a lambda expression consists of the keyword `lambda`, followed by a parameter list like that of a `def` statement but unparenthesized, then a colon `:`, and a single expression, the *function body*.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] As with functions created by a `def` statement, a lambda function captures the syntax of its body, the default values of any optional parameters, a reference to each free variable appearing in its body, and the global dictionary of the current module.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The name of a function created by a lambda expression is `"lambda"`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p02] The two statements below are essentially equivalent, but the function created by the `def` statement is named `twice` and the function created by the lambda expression is named `lambda`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Use a `pass` statement when the syntax requires a statement but no behavior is required, such as the body of a function that does nothing.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] An assignment statement has the form `lhs = rhs`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] It evaluates the expression on the right-hand side then assigns its value (or values) to the variable (or variables) on the left-hand side.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The expression on the left-hand side is called a *target*.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The simplest target is the name of a variable, but a target may also have the form of a subscript expression to update the element of a list or dictionary, or the form of a dot expression to update the field of an object.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Compound targets may consist of a comma-separated list of subtargets, optionally surrounded by parentheses or square brackets.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] An assignment to a compound target checks that the right-hand value is a sequence with the same number of elements as the target.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Each element of the sequence is then assigned to the corresponding element of the target, recursively applying the same logic.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The same process for assigning a value to a target expression is used in `for` statements and in comprehension `for` clauses.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] An augmented assignment, which has the form `lhs op= rhs` updates the variable `lhs` by applying a binary arithmetic operator `op` (one of `+`, `-`, `*`, `/`, `//`, `%`, `&`, `|`, `^`, `<<`, `>>`) to the previous value of `lhs` and the value of `rhs`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The left-hand side must be a simple target: a name, a subscript expression, or a dot expression.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Any subexpressions in the target on the left-hand side are evaluated exactly once, before the evaluation of `rhs`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] A `def` statement creates a named function and assigns it to a variable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The function's name is preceded by the `def` keyword and followed by the parameter list (which is enclosed in parentheses), a colon, and then an indented block of statements which form the body of the function.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The parameter list is a comma-separated list whose elements are of several kinds.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] First come zero or more required parameters, which are simple identifiers; all calls must provide an argument value for these parameters.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The required parameters are followed by zero or more optional parameters, of the form `name=expression`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The expression specifies the default value for the parameter for use in calls that do not provide an argument value for it.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The required parameters are optionally followed by a single parameter name preceded by a `*`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] This is the called the *varargs* parameter, and it accumulates surplus positional arguments specified by a call.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The varargs parameter may be followed by zero or more parameters, again of the forms `name` or `name=expression`, but these parameters differ from earlier ones in that they are *keyword-only*: if a call provides their values, it must do so as keyword arguments, not positional ones.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Note that even though keyword-only arguments are declared after `*args` in a function's definition, they nevertheless must appear before `*args` in a call to the function.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] A non-variadic function may also declare keyword-only parameters, by using a bare `*` in place of the `*args` parameter.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] This form does not declare a parameter but marks the boundary between the earlier parameters and the keyword-only parameters.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] This form must be followed by at least one optional parameter.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Finally, there may be an optional parameter name preceded by `**`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] This is called the *keyword arguments* parameter, and accumulates in a dictionary any surplus `name=value` arguments that do not match a prior parameter.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Execution of a `def` statement creates a new function object.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The function object contains: the syntax of the function body; the default value for each optional parameter; a reference to each free variable appearing within the function body; and the global dictionary of the current module.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] A `return` statement ends the execution of a function and returns a value to the caller of the function.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] A return statement may have zero, one, or more result expressions separated by commas.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] With no expressions, the function has the result `None`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] With a single expression, the function's result is the value of that expression.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] With multiple expressions, the function's result is a tuple.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] An expression statement evaluates an expression and discards its result.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Any expression may be used as a statement, but an expression statement is most often used to call a function for its side effects.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] An `if` statement evaluates an expression (the *condition*), then, if the truth value of the condition is `True`, executes a list of statements.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] An `if` statement may have an `else` block defining a second list of statements to be executed if the condition is false.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] It is common for the `else` block to contain another `if` statement.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] An `if` statement is permitted only within a function definition.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] An `if` statement at top level results in a static error.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] A `for` statement evaluates its operand, which must be an iterable value.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Then, for each element of the iterable, the loop assigns the successive element values to one or more variables and executes a list of statements, the *loop body*.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The assignment of each value to the loop variables follows the same rules as an ordinary assignment.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Because Starlark loops always iterate over a finite iterable (assuming the host application does not define an unbounded type), they are guaranteed to terminate, unlike loops in most languages which can execute an arbitrary and perhaps unbounded number of iterations.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Within the body of a `for` loop, `break` and `continue` statements may be used to stop the execution of the loop or advance to the next iteration.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] In Starlark, a `for` statement is permitted only within a function definition.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] A `for` statement at top level results in a static error.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The `break` and `continue` statements terminate the current iteration of a `for` statement.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Whereas the `continue` statement resumes the loop at the next iteration, a `break` statement terminates the entire loop.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Both statements affect only the innermost lexically enclosing loop.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] It is a static error to use a `break` or `continue` statement outside a loop.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The `load` statement loads another Starlark module, extracts one or more values from it, and binds them to names in the current module.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Syntactically, a load statement looks like a function call `load(...)`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] A load statement requires at least two "arguments".
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The first must be a literal string; it identifies the module to load.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Its interpretation is determined by the application into which the Starlark interpreter is embedded, and is not specified here.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] During execution, the application determines what action to take for a load statement.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] A typical implementation locates and executes a Starlark file, populating a cache of files executed so far to avoid duplicate work, to obtain a module, which is a mapping from global names to values.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The remaining arguments are a mixture of literal strings, such as `"x"`, or named literal strings, such as `y="x"`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The literal string (`"x"`), which must denote a valid identifier not starting with `_`, specifies the name to extract from the loaded module.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] In effect, names starting with `_` are not exported.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The name (`y`) specifies the local name; if no name is given, the local name matches the quoted name.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] A load statement within a function is a static error.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Each Starlark file defines a *module*, which is a mapping from the names of global variables to their values.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] When a Starlark file is executed, whether directly by the application or indirectly through a `load` statement, a new Starlark thread is created, and this thread executes all the top-level statements in the file.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Because `if` statements and `for` statements cannot appear outside of a function, control flows from top to bottom.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] If execution reaches the end of the file, module initialization is successful.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] At that point, the value of each of the module's global variables is frozen, rendering subsequent mutation impossible.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The module is then ready for use by another Starlark thread, such as one executing a load statement.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Such threads may access values or call functions defined in the loaded module.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] A Starlark thread may carry state on behalf of the application into which it is embedded, and application-defined functions may behave differently depending on this thread state.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Because module initialization always occurs in a new thread, thread state is never carried from a higher-level module into a lower-level one.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The initialization behavior of a module is thus independent of whichever module triggered its initialization.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] If a Starlark thread encounters an error, execution stops and the error is reported to the application, along with a backtrace showing the stack of active function calls at the time of the error.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] If an error occurs during initialization of a Starlark module, any active `load` statements waiting for initialization of the module also fail.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Starlark provides no mechanism by which errors can be handled within the language.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The outermost block of the Starlark environment is known as the "predeclared" block.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] It defines a number of fundamental values and functions needed by all Starlark programs, such as `None`, `True`, `False`, and `len`, and possibly additional application-specific names.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] These names are not reserved words so Starlark programs are free to redefine them in a smaller block such as a function body or even at the top level of a module.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] However, doing so may be confusing to the reader.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Nonetheless, this rule permits names to be added to the predeclared block in later versions of the language (or application-specific dialect) without breaking existing programs.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] As with built-in functions, built-in methods accept only positional arguments except where noted.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The parameter names serve merely as documentation.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `None` is the distinguished value of the type `NoneType`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `True` and `False` are the two values of type `bool`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `abs(x)` takes either an integer or a float, and returns the absolute value of that number (a non-negative number with the same magnitude).
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `any(x)` returns `True` if any element of the collection `x` is true.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] If the collection is empty, it returns `False`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `all(x)` returns `False` if any element of the collection `x` is false.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] If the collection is empty, it returns `True`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `bool(x)` interprets `x` as a Boolean value---`True` or `False`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] With no argument, `bool()` returns `False`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `bytes(x)` converts its argument to a `bytes`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] If x is a string, the result is a `bytes` whose elements are the UTF-8 encoding of the string.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Each element of the string that is not part of a valid encoding of a code point is replaced by the UTF-8 encoding of the replacement character, U+FFFD.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] If x is an iterable of int values, the result is a `bytes` whose elements are those integers.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] It is an error if any element is not in the range 0-255.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] It accepts up to one positional argument, which is interpreted as an iterable of two-element sequences (pairs), each specifying a key/value pair in the resulting dictionary.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `dict` also accepts any number of keyword arguments, each of which specifies a key/value pair in the resulting dictionary; each keyword is treated as a string.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] With no arguments, `dict()` returns a new empty dictionary.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `dict(x)` where x is a dictionary returns a new copy of x.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `dir(x)` returns a new sorted list of the names of the attributes (fields and methods) of its operand.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The attributes of a value `x` are the names `f` such that `x.f` is a valid expression.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Several types known to the interpreter, such as list, string, and dict, have methods, but none have fields.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `enumerate(x)` returns a list consisting of pairs `(i, v)`, where each successive `v` is the next item of collection `x`, and where `i` starts at 0 and is incremented sequentially.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The optional second parameter, `start`, specifies an integer value to add to each index.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The `fail(*args)` function causes execution to fail with an error message that includes the string forms of the argument values.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The precise formatting depends on the implementation.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `float(x)` interprets its argument as a floating-point number.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] If x is an `int`, the result is the floating-point value nearest x.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The call fails if x is too large to represent as a finite `float`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] If x is a `bool`, the result is `1.0` for `True` and `0.0` for `False`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] If x is a string, the string is interpreted as a floating-point literal.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The function also recognizes the names `Inf` (or `Infinity`) and `NaN`, optionally preceded by a `+` or `-` sign.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] These construct the IEEE 754 non-finite values.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The call fails if the literal denotes a value too large to represent as a finite `float`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] With no argument, `float()` returns `0.0`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `getattr(x, name[, default])` returns the value of the attribute (field or method) of x named `name` if it exists.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] If not, it either returns `default` (if specified) or raises an error.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `getattr(x, "f")` is equivalent to `x.f`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The three-argument form `getattr(x, name, default)` returns the provided `default` value instead of failing.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `hasattr(x, name)` reports whether x has an attribute (field or method) named `name`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `hash(x)` returns an integer hash of a string or bytes x such that two equal values have the same hash.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] In other words `x == y` implies `hash(x) == hash(y)`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Any other type of argument in an error, even if it is suitable as the key of a dict.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `int(x[, base])` interprets its argument as an integer.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] If x is a `float`, the result is the integer value nearest to x, truncating towards zero.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] It is an error if x is not finite (`NaN` or infinity).
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] If x is a `bool`, the result is 0 for `False` or 1 for `True`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] If x is a string, it is interpreted as a sequence of digits in the specified base, decimal by default.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] If `base` is zero, x is interpreted like an integer literal, the base being inferred from an optional base prefix such as `0b`, `0o`, or `0x` preceding the first digit.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] When a nonzero `base` is provided explicitly, its value must be between 2 and 36.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The letters `a-z` represent the digits 11 through 35.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] A matching base prefix is also permitted, and has no effect.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Irrespective of base, the string may start with an optional `+` or `-`, indicating the sign of the result.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `len(x)` returns the number of elements in its argument.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] It is a dynamic error if its argument is not a collection, string, or bytes.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `list(x)` returns a new list containing the elements of the iterable `x`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] With no argument, `list()` returns a new empty list.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `max(x)` returns the greatest element in the collection `x`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] It is an error if any element does not support ordered comparison, or if the collection is empty.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The optional named parameter `key` specifies a function to be applied to each element, whose result is used for the comparison in place of the element.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `min(x)` returns the least element in the collection `x`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `print(*args, sep=" ")` prints its arguments, followed by a newline.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Arguments are formatted as if by `str(x)` and separated with a space, unless an alternative separator is specified by a `sep` named argument.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Typically the formatted string is printed to the standard error file, but the exact behavior is a property of the Starlark thread and is determined by the host application.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `range` returns an immutable sequence of integers defined by the specified interval and stride.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `range` requires between one and three integer arguments.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] With one argument, `range(stop)` returns the ascending sequence of non-negative integers less than `stop`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] With two arguments, `range(start, stop)` returns only integers not less than `start`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] With three arguments, `range(start, stop, step)` returns integers formed by successively adding `step` to `start` until the value meets or passes `stop`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] A call to `range` fails if the value of `step` is zero.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] A call to `range` does not materialize the entire sequence, but returns a fixed-size value of type `"range"` that represents the parameters that define the sequence.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The `range` value is iterable and may be indexed efficiently.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The `len` function applied to a `range` value returns its length.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The truth value of a `range` value is `True` if its length is non-zero.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Range values are comparable: two `range` values compare equal if they denote the same sequence of integers, even if they were created using different parameters.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The `str` function applied to a `range` value yields a string of the form `range(10)`, `range(1, 10)`, or `range(1, 10, 2)`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The `x in y` operator, where `y` is a range, reports whether `x` is equal to some member of the sequence `y`; the operation fails unless `x` is a number.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `repr(x)` formats its argument as a string.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] All strings in the result are double-quoted.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] When applied to a string containing valid text, `repr` returns a string literal that denotes that string.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] When applied to a string containing an invalid UTF-K sequence, `repr` uses `\x` and `\u` escapes with out-of-range values to indicate the invalid elements; the result is not a valid literal.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `reversed(x)` returns a new list containing the elements of the collection `x` in reverse order.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `set(x)` returns a new set containing the unique elements of the iterable `x` in iteration order.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `set(x)` fails if any element of `x` is unhashable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] With no argument, `set()` returns a new empty set.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `sorted(x)` returns a new list containing the elements of the collection x, in sorted order.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The sort algorithm is stable, i.e., equal elements appear in the same relative order in the result.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The optional named boolean parameter `reverse`, if true, causes `sorted` to return results in reverse sorted order.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The optional named parameter `key` specifies a function of one argument to apply to obtain the value's sort key.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The default behavior is the identity function.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The `key` function is called exactly once per element of the sequence, in order, even for a single-element list.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `str(x)` formats its argument as a string.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] If x is a string, the result is x (without quotation).
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] All other strings, such as elements of a list of strings, are double-quoted.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The string form of a bytes value is the UTF-K decoding of the bytes.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] Each byte that is not part of a valid encoding is replaced by the UTF-K encoding of the replacement character, U+FFFD.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `tuple(x)` returns a tuple containing the elements of the iterable `x`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] With no arguments, `tuple()` returns the empty tuple.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `type(x)` returns a string describing the type of its operand.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] `zip()` returns a new list of n-tuples formed from corresponding elements of each of the n collections provided as arguments to `zip`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] That is, the first tuple contains the first element of each of the collections, the second element contains the second element of each of the collections, and so on.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p03] The result list is only as long as the shortest of the input collections.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] This section lists the methods of built-in types.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] Methods are selected using dot expressions.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] For example, strings have a `count` method that counts occurrences of a substring; `"banana".count("a")` yields `3`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `b.elems()` returns an opaque iterable value containing successive int elements of b.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] Its type is `"bytes.elems"`, and its string representation is of the form `b"...".elems()`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `D.clear()` removes all the entries of dictionary D and returns `None`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] It fails if the dictionary is frozen or if there are active iterators.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `D.get(key[, default])` returns the dictionary value corresponding to the given key.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If the dictionary contains no such value, `get` returns `None`, or the value of the optional `default` parameter if present.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `get` fails if `key` is unhashable, or the dictionary is frozen or has active iterators.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `D.items()` returns a new list of key/value pairs, one per element in dictionary D, in the same order as they would be returned by a `for` loop.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `D.keys()` returns a new list containing the keys of dictionary D, in the same order as they would be returned by a `for` loop.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `D.pop(key[, default])` returns the value corresponding to the specified key, and removes it from the dictionary.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If the dictionary contains no such value, and the optional `default` parameter is present, `pop` returns that value; otherwise, it fails.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `pop` fails if `key` is unhashable, or the dictionary is frozen or has active iterators.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `D.popitem()` returns the first key/value pair, removing it from the dictionary.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `popitem` fails if the dictionary is empty, frozen, or has active iterators.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `D.setdefault(key[, default])` returns the dictionary value corresponding to the given key.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If the dictionary contains no such value, `setdefault`, like `get`, returns `None` or the value of the optional `default` parameter if present; `setdefault` additionally inserts the new key/value entry into the dictionary.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `setdefault` fails if the key is unhashable, or if the dictionary is frozen or has active iterators.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If the positional argument `pairs` is present, it must be `None`, another `dict`, or some other iterable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If it is another `dict`, then its key/value pairs are inserted into D.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If it is an iterable, it must provide a sequence of pairs (or other iterables of length 2), each of which is treated as a key/value pair to be inserted into D.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] Then, for each `name=value` argument present, an entry with key `name` and value `value` is inserted into D.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] All insertions overwrite any previous entries having the same key.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] It is permissible to update the dict with itself given as pairs.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `update` fails if the dictionary is frozen or has active iterators.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `D.values()` returns a new list containing the dictionary's values, in the same order as they would be returned by a `for` loop over the dictionary.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `L.append(x)` appends `x` to the list L, and returns `None`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `append` fails if the list is frozen or has active iterators.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `L.clear()` removes all the elements of the list L and returns `None`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] It fails if the list is frozen or if there are active iterators.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `L.extend(x)` appends the elements of `x`, which must be iterable, to the list L, and returns `None`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] It is permissible to extend the list with itself.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `extend` fails if `x` is not iterable, or if the list L is frozen or has active iterators.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `L.index(x[, start[, end]])` finds `x` within the list L and returns its index.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] The optional `start` and `end` parameters restrict the portion of list L that is inspected.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If provided and not `None`, they must be list indices of type `int`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If an index is negative, `len(L)` is effectively added to it, then if the index is outside the range `[0:len(L)]`, the nearest value within that range is used; see Indexing.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `index` fails if `x` is not found in L, or if `start` or `end` is not a valid index (`int` or `None`).
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] To avoid this error, test `x in list` before calling `list.index(x)`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `L.insert(i, x)` inserts the value `x` in the list L at index `i`, moving higher-numbered elements along by one.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] As usual, the index `i` must be an `int`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If its value is negative, the length of the list is added, then its value is clamped to the nearest value in the range `[0:len(L)]` to yield the effective index.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `insert` fails if the list is frozen or has active iterators.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `L.pop([index])` removes and returns the last element of the list L, or, if the optional index is provided, at that index.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `pop` fails if the index is negative or not less than the length of the list, of if the list is frozen or has active iterators.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `L.remove(x)` removes the first occurrence of the value `x` from the list L, and returns `None`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `remove` fails if the list does not contain `x`, is frozen, or has active iterators.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.add(x)` adds the value `x` to the set `S`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] It is permissible to `add` a value already present in the set; this leaves the set `S` unchanged.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `add` fails if the set `S` is frozen or has active iterators, or if `x` is unhashable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If you need to add multiple elements to a set, see `update` or the `|=` augmented assignment operation.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.clear()` removes all elements from the set `S`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `clear` fails if the set `S` is frozen or has active iterators.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.difference(*others)` returns a new set containing elements found in the set `S` but not found in any of the collections `*others`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If `s` and `t` are sets, `s.difference(t)` is equivalent to `s - t`; however, note that the `-` operation requires both sides to be sets, while the `difference` method accepts arbitrary collections.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] It is permissible to call `difference` without any arguments; this returns a copy of the set `S`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `difference` fails if any element of any of the `*others` is unhashable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.difference_update(*others)` removes from the set `S` any elements found in any of the collections `*others`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If `s` and `t` are sets, `s.difference_update(t)` is equivalent to `s -= t`; however, note that the `-=` augmented assignment requires both sides to be sets, while the `difference_update` method accepts arbitrary collections.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] It is permissible to call `difference_update` without any arguments; this leaves the set `S` unchanged.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `difference_update` fails if the set `S` is frozen or has active iterators, or if any element of any of the `*others` is unhashable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.discard(x)` removes the value `x` from the set `S` if present.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] It is permissible to `discard` a value not present in the set; this leaves the set `S` unchanged.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If you want to fail on an attempt to remove a non-present element, use `remove` instead.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If you need to remove multiple elements from a set, see `difference_update` or the `-=` augmented assignment operation.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `discard` fails if the set `S` is frozen or has active iterators, or if `x` is unhashable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] This applies even if `x` is not a member of the set.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.intersection(*others)` returns a new set containing those elements that the set `S` and all of the collections `*others` have in common.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If `s` and `t` are sets, `s.intersection(t)` is equivalent to `s & t`; however, note that the `&` operation requires both sides to be sets, while the `intersection` method accepts arbitrary collections.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] It is permissible to call `intersection` without any arguments; this returns a copy of the set `S`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `intersection` fails if any element of any of the `*others` is unhashable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.intersection_update(*others)` removes from the set `S` any elements not found in at least one of the collections `*others`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If `s` and `t` are sets, `s.intersection_update(t)` is equivalent to `s &= t`; however, note that the `&=` augmented assignment requires both sides to be sets, while the `intersection_update` method accepts arbitrary collections.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] It is permissible to call `intersection_update` without any arguments; this leaves the set `S` unchanged.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `intersection_update` fails if the set `S` is frozen or has active iterators, or if any element of any of the `*others` is unhashable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.isdisjoint(x)` returns `True` if the set `S` and the collection `x` do not have any values in common, and `False` otherwise.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] This is equivalent to `not S.intersection(x)`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `isdisjoint` fails if any element of `x` is unhashable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.issubset(x)` returns `True` if every element of the set `S` is present in the collection `x`, and `False` otherwise.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] This is equivalent to `not S.difference(x)`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `issubset` fails if any element of `x` is unhashable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.issuperset(x)` returns `True` if every element of the collection `x` is present in the set `S`, and `False` otherwise.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] This is equivalent to `S == S.union(x)`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `issuperset` fails if any element of `x` is unhashable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.pop()` removes and returns the first element (in iteration order, which is the order in which elements were first added to the set) from the set `S`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `pop` fails if the set is empty, is frozen, or has active iterators.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.remove(x)` removes the value `x` from the set `S`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `remove` fails if the set doesn't contain `x` (which, in particular, implies that `remove` fails if `x` is unhashable), or if the set is frozen or has active iterators.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If you don't want to fail on an attempt to remove a non-present element, use `discard` instead.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.symmetric_difference(x)` returns a new set containing elements found only in the set `S` or in the collection `x` but not those found in both `S` and `x`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If `s` and `t` are sets, `s.symmetric_difference(t)` is equivalent to `s ^ t`; however, note that the `^` operation requires both sides to be sets, while the `symmetric_difference` method accepts an arbitrary collection.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `symmetric_difference` fails if any element of `x` is unhashable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.symmetric_difference_update(x)` removes from the set `S` any elements found in both `S` and the collection `x`, and adds to `S` any elements found in `x` but not in `S`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If `s` and `t` are sets, `s.symmetric_difference_update(t)` is equivalent to `s ^= t`; however, note that the `^=` augmented assignment requires both sides to be sets, while the `symmetric_difference_update` method accepts an arbitrary collection.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `symmetric_difference_update` fails if the set `S` is frozen or has active iterators, or if any element of `x` is unhashable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.union(*others)` returns a new set containing elements found in the set `S` or in any of the collections `*others`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If `s` and `t` are sets, `s.union(t)` is equivalent to `s | t`; however, note that the `|` operation requires both sides to be sets, while the `union` method accepts arbitrary collections.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] It is permissible to call `union` without any arguments; this returns a copy of the set `S`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `union` fails if any element of any of the `*others` is unhashable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.update(*others)` adds to the set `S` any elements found in any of the collections `*others`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If `s` and `t` are sets, `s.update(t)` is equivalent to `s |= t`; however, note that the `|=` augmented assignment requires both sides to be sets, while the `update` method accepts arbitrary collections.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] It is permissible to call `update` without any arguments; this leaves the set `S` unchanged.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `update` fails if the set `S` is frozen or has active iterators, or if any element of any of the `*others` is unhashable.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.capitalize()` returns a copy of string S, where the first character (if any) is converted to uppercase; all other characters are converted to lowercase.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.count(sub[, start[, end]])` returns the number of occurrences of `sub` within the string S, or, if the optional substring indices `start` and `end` are provided, within the designated substring of S.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] They are interpreted according to Starlark's indexing conventions.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.elems()` returns an opaque iterable value containing successive 1-element substrings of S.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] Its type is `"string.elems"`, and its string representation is of the form `"...".elems()`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.endswith(suffix[, start[, end]])` reports whether the string `S[start:end]` has the specified suffix.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] The `suffix` argument may be a tuple of strings, in which case the function reports whether any one of them is a suffix.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.find(sub[, start[, end]])` returns the index of the first occurrence of the substring `sub` within S.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If either or both of `start` or `end` are specified, they specify a subrange of S to which the search should be restricted.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If no occurrence is found, `found` returns -1.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.format(*args, **kwargs)` returns a version of the format string S in which bracketed portions `{...}` are replaced by arguments from `args` and `kwargs`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] Within the format string, a pair of braces `{{` or `}}` is treated as a literal open or close brace.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] Each unpaired open brace must be matched by a close brace `}`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] The optional text between corresponding open and close braces specifies which argument to use.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] The *field name* may be either a decimal number or a keyword.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] A number is interpreted as the index of a positional argument; a keyword specifies the value of a keyword argument.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If all the numeric field names form the sequence 0, 1, 2, and so on, they may be omitted and those values will be implied; however, the explicit and implicit forms may not be mixed.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.index(sub[, start[, end]])` returns the index of the first occurrence of the substring `sub` within S, like `S.find`, except that if the substring is not found, the operation fails.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.isalnum()` reports whether the string S is non-empty and consists only Unicode letters and digits.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.isalpha()` reports whether the string S is non-empty and consists only of Unicode letters.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.isdigit()` reports whether the string S is non-empty and consists only of Unicode digits.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.islower()` reports whether the string S contains at least one cased Unicode letter, and all such letters are lowercase.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.isspace()` reports whether the string S is non-empty and consists only of Unicode spaces.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.istitle()` reports whether the string S contains at least one cased Unicode letter, and all such letters that begin a word are in title case.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.isupper()` reports whether the string S contains at least one cased Unicode letter, and all such letters are uppercase.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.join(iterable)` returns the string formed by concatenating each element of its argument, with a copy of the string S between successive elements.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] The argument must be an iterable whose elements are strings.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.lower()` returns a copy of the string S with letters converted to lowercase.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.lstrip([cutset])` returns a copy of the string S with leading whitespace removed.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] Like `strip`, it accepts an optional string parameter that specifies an alternative set of Unicode code points to remove.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.partition(x)` splits string S into three parts and returns them as a tuple: the portion before the first occurrence of string `x`, `x` itself, and the portion following it.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If S does not contain `x`, `partition` returns `(S, "", "")`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `partition` fails if `x` is not a string, or is the empty string.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.removeprefix(x)` removes the prefix `x` from the string S at most once, and returns the rest of the string.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If the prefix string is not found then it returns the original string.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `removeprefix` fails if `x` is not a string.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.removesuffix(x)` removes the suffix `x` from the string S at most once, and returns the rest of the string.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If the suffix string is not found then it returns the original string.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `removesuffix` fails if `x` is not a string.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.replace(old, new[, count])` returns a copy of string S with all occurrences of substring `old` replaced by `new`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If the optional argument `count`, which must be an `int`, is non-negative, it specifies a maximum number of occurrences to replace.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.rfind(sub[, start[, end]])` returns the index of the substring `sub` within S, like `S.find`, except that `rfind` returns the index of the substring's *last* occurrence.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.rindex(sub[, start[, end]])` returns the index of the substring `sub` within S, like `S.index`, except that `rindex` returns the index of the substring's *last* occurrence.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.rpartition(x)` is like `partition`, but splits `S` at the last occurrence of `x`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.rsplit([sep[, maxsplit]])` splits a string into substrings like `S.split`, except that when a maximum number of splits is specified, `rsplit` chooses the rightmost splits.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.rstrip([cutset])` returns a copy of the string S with trailing whitespace removed.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.split([sep [, maxsplit]])` returns the list of substrings of S, splitting at occurrences of the delimiter string `sep`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] Consecutive occurrences of `sep` are considered to delimit empty strings, so `'food'.split('o')` returns `['f', '', 'd']`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] Splitting an empty string with a specified separator returns `['']`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If `sep` is the empty string, `split` fails.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If `sep` is not specified or is `None`, `split` uses a different algorithm: it removes all leading spaces from S (or trailing spaces in the case of `rsplit`), then splits the string around each consecutive non-empty sequence of Unicode white space characters.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If S consists only of white space, `split` returns the empty list.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If `maxsplit` is given and non-negative, it specifies a maximum number of splits.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.splitlines([keepends])` returns a list whose elements are the successive lines of S, that is, the strings formed by splitting S at line terminators (currently assumed to be `\n`, `\r` and `\r\n`, regardless of platform).
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] The optional argument, `keepends`, is interpreted as a Boolean.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] If true, line terminators are preserved in the result, though the final element does not necessarily end with a line terminator.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.startswith(prefix[, start[, end]])` reports whether the string `S[start:end]` has the specified prefix.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] The `prefix` argument may be a tuple of strings, in which case the function reports whether any one of them is a prefix.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.strip([cutset])` returns a copy of the string S with leading and trailing whitespace removed.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] It accepts an optional string argument, `cutset`, which instead removes all leading and trailing Unicode code points contained in `cutset`.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.title()` returns a copy of the string S with letters converted to titlecase.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] Letters are converted to uppercase at the start of words, lowercase elsewhere.
[src:starlark/blob-spec-md-p04] `S.upper()` returns a copy of the string S with letters converted to uppercase.
[src:starlark/build-automation] Build automation encompasses both sequencing build operations via non-interactive interface tools and running builds on a shared server.
[src:starlark/build-automation] Build automation tools allow sequencing the tasks of building software via a non-interactive interface.
[src:starlark/build-automation] A *build system* or *build automation tool* is a programming tool or set of tools that automate the compiling and linking of source code into an executable program or library.
[src:starlark/build-automation] They streamline the software development process by managing dependencies, resolving conflicts, and ensuring consistent builds across different environments.
[src:starlark/build-automation] When software projects grow complex, their build steps may involve multiple programming languages or compiling units, making manual build processes increasingly cumbersome.
[src:starlark/build-automation] Dependencies between code components necessitate careful ordering and potentially different tools for each piece.
[src:starlark/build-automation] Managing these dependencies manually can quickly lead to version conflicts, stale binaries, and difficulty tracking updates, making solutions such as shell scripts too difficult to maintain.
[src:starlark/build-automation] While individual developers might compile code directly, a robust build system is foundational to efficient software development in large organizations and teams, where automated builds become commonplace and most builds are triggered automatically rather than manually.
[src:starlark/build-automation] Given the essential role of build systems, it is said that they act as "repositories of essential build knowledge".
[src:starlark/build-automation] They effectively eliminate roadblocks and accelerate development velocity by enabling engineers to share resources and results.
[src:starlark/build-automation] An incremental build is a process within a build system where build tools use an incremental compiler to recompile only the parts of a software project that have changed since the last build, rather than rebuilding everything from scratch.
[src:starlark/build-automation] This optimization reduces build time by leveraging dependency tracking, caching, and selective compilation.
[src:starlark/build-automation] Incremental builds are especially valuable in large-scale software projects, where recompiling the entire codebase can be time-consuming and resource-intensive.
[src:starlark/build-automation] By identifying and compiling only the modified components—such as source files, libraries, or modules—the build system ensures faster iteration cycles, enabling developers to test and debug changes more efficiently.
[src:starlark/build-automation] The process relies on a dependency graph, which maps relationships between files, modules, or components in the project.
[src:starlark/build-automation] When a change is detected, the build system traverses this graph to determine which parts of the project are affected and need to be recompiled.
[src:starlark/build-automation] Modern build tools, such as Make, Gradle and Bazel, often incorporate incremental build capabilities to streamline development workflows.
[src:starlark/build-automation] While incremental builds offer significant performance advantages, they also introduce challenges, such as ensuring the accuracy of dependency tracking and avoiding stale or inconsistent build artifacts.
[src:starlark/build-automation] To address these issues, some build systems provide mechanisms for "clean builds," which rebuild the entire project from scratch to guarantee correctness when necessary.
[src:starlark/build-automation] Because of this issue, incremental builds are rarely used in continuous integration systems, where correctness is preferred to compilation speed.
[src:starlark/build-automation] Tools such as Make can be used via custom configuration file or using the command-line.
[src:starlark/build-automation] Custom tools such as shell scripts can also be used, although they become increasingly cumbersome as the codebase grows more complex.
[src:starlark/build-automation] Some tools, such as shell scripts, are task-oriented declarative programming.
[src:starlark/build-automation] They encode sequences of commands to perform with usually minimal conditional logic.
[src:starlark/build-automation] Some tools, such as Make are product-oriented.
[src:starlark/build-automation] They build a product, a.k.a. target, based on configured dependencies.
[src:starlark/build-automation] A build server is a server setup to run builds.
[src:starlark/build-automation] In contrast to a personal computer, a server allows for a more consistent and available build environment.
[src:starlark/build-automation] Traditionally, a build server was a local computer dedicated as a shared resource instead of used as a personal computer.
[src:starlark/build-automation] Today, there are many cloud computing, software as a service (SaaS) websites for building.
[src:starlark/build-automation] A continuous integration server is a build server that is setup to build in a relatively frequent way, often on each code commit.
[src:starlark/build-automation] A build server may also be incorporated into a tool for application release automation (ARA) or application lifecycle management (ALM).
[src:starlark/build-automation] Automating the build process is a required step for implementing continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD), all of which are considered best practices for software development.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] In computer science, **declarative programming** is a programming paradigm that expresses the logic of a computation without fully describing its control flow.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] This is in contrast with imperative programming, which implements algorithms in explicit steps.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Declarative programming may consider programs as theories of a formal logic, and computations as deductions in that logical theory.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Declarative programming at times simplifies the writing of parallel programs.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Common declarative language paradigms include logic programming (e.g., Prolog, Datalog, answer set programming), and algebraic modeling systems.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is often defined as any style of programming that is not imperative.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] A number of other common definitions attempt to define it by simply contrasting it with imperative programming.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] These definitions overlap substantially.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is a non-imperative style of programming in which programs describe their desired results without explicitly listing commands or steps that must be performed.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages are characterized by a mostly declarative programming style.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] In logic programming, programs consist of sentences expressed in logical form, and computation uses those sentences to solve problems, which are also expressed in logical form.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] In a pure functional language, such as Haskell, all functions are without side effects, and state changes are only represented as functions that transform the state, which is explicitly represented as a first-class object in the program.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Although pure functional languages are non-imperative, they often provide a facility for describing the effect of a function as a series of steps.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Other functional languages, such as Lisp, OCaml and Erlang, support a mixture of procedural and functional programming.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Some logic programming languages, such as Prolog, and database query languages, such as SQL, while declarative in principle, also support a procedural style of programming.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is an umbrella term that includes a number of better-known programming paradigms.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Constraint programming states relations between variables in the form of constraints that specify the properties of the target solution.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] The set of constraints is solved by giving a value to each variable so that the solution is consistent with the maximum number of constraints.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Constraint programming often complements other paradigms: functional, logical, or even imperative programming.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Makefiles, for example, specify dependencies in a declarative fashion, but include an imperative list of actions to take as well.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Similarly, yacc specifies a context free grammar declaratively, but includes code snippets from a host language, which is usually imperative (such as C).
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages, such as Prolog, Datalog and answer set programming, compute by proving that a goal is a logical consequence of the program, or by showing that the goal is true in a model defined by the program.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Prolog computes by reducing goals to subgoals, top-down using backward reasoning, whereas most Datalog systems compute bottom-up using forward reasoning.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Answer set programs typically use SAT solvers to generate a model of the program.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Models, or mathematical representations, of physical systems may be implemented in computer code that is declarative.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] The code contains a number of equations, not imperative assignments, that describe ("declare") the behavioral relationships.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] When a model is expressed in this formalism, a computer is able to perform algebraic manipulations to best formulate the solution algorithm.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] The mathematical causality is typically imposed at the boundaries of the physical system, while the behavioral description of the system itself is declarative or acausal.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Declarative modeling languages and environments include Analytica, Modelica and Simile.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Prolog (1972) stands for "PROgramming in LOGic." It was developed for natural language question answering, using SL resolution both to deduce answers to queries and to parse and generate natural language sentences.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] The building blocks of a Prolog program are *facts* and *rules*.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Given this program, the query `eat(tom,jerry)` succeeds, while `eat(jerry,tom)` fails.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Moreover, the query `eat(X,jerry)` succeeds with the answer substitution `X=tom`.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Prolog executes programs top-down, using SLD resolution to reason backwards, reducing goals to subgoals.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] In this example, it uses the last rule of the program to reduce the goal of answering the query `eat(X,jerry)` to the subgoals of first finding an X such that `big(X)` holds and then of showing that `small(jerry)` holds.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] It repeatedly uses rules to further reduce subgoals to other subgoals, until it eventually succeeds in unifying all subgoals with facts in the program.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] This backward reasoning, goal-reduction strategy treats rules in logic programs as procedures, and makes Prolog both a declarative and procedural programming language.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] The broad range of Prolog applications is highlighted in the Year of Prolog Book, celebrating the 50 year anniversary of Prolog.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] The origins of Datalog date back to the beginning of logic programming, but it was identified as a separate area around 1977.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Syntactically and semantically, it is a subset of Prolog.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] But because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Most Datalog systems execute programs bottom-up, using rules to reason forwards, deriving new facts from existing facts, and terminating when there are no new facts that can be derived, or when the derived facts unify with the query.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Datalog has been applied to such problems as data integration, information extraction, networking, security, cloud computing and machine learning.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Answer set programming (ASP) evolved in the late 1990s, based on the stable model (answer set) semantics of logic programming.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Like Datalog, it is a subset of Prolog; and, because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Most implementations of ASP execute a program by first *grounding* the program, replacing all variables in rules by constants in all possible ways, and then using a propositional SAT solver, such as the DPLL algorithm to generate one or more models of the program.
[src:starlark/declarative-programming] Its applications are oriented towards solving difficult search problems and knowledge representation.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] A **domain-specific language** (**DSL**) is a computer language specialized to a specific application domain.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] This is in contrast to a general-purpose language (GPL), which is broadly applicable across domains.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] There are a wide variety of DSLs, ranging from widely used languages for common domains, such as HTML for web pages, down to languages used by only one or a few pieces of software, such as MUSH soft code.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] DSLs can be further subdivided by the kind of language, and include domain-specific *markup* languages, domain-specific *modeling* languages (more generally, specification languages), and domain-specific *programming* languages.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Special-purpose computer languages have always existed in the computer age, but the term "domain-specific language" has become more popular due to the rise of domain-specific modeling.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Simpler DSLs, specifically ones used by a single application, are sometimes informally called **mini-languages**.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] For example, Perl was originally developed as a text-processing and glue language, for the same domain as AWK and shell scripts, but was mostly used as a general-purpose programming language later on.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] In contrast, PostScript is a Turing-complete language, and in principle can be used for any task, but in practice is narrowly used as a page description language.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] The design and use of appropriate DSLs is a key part of domain engineering, by using a language suitable to the domain at hand – this may consist of using an existing DSL or GPL, or developing a new DSL.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Language-oriented programming considers the creation of special-purpose languages for expressing problems as standard part of the problem-solving process.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Pragmatically, a DSL may be specialized to a specific problem domain, a specific problem representation technique, a specific solution technique, or other aspects of a domain.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language is created specifically to solve problems in a specific domain and is not intended to be able to solve problems outside of it (although that may be technically possible).
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] In contrast, general-purpose languages are created to solve problems in many domains.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language is somewhere between a tiny programming language and a scripting language, and is often used in a way analogous to a programming library.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] The boundaries between these concepts are quite blurry, much like the boundary between scripting languages and general-purpose languages.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific languages are languages (or often, declared syntaxes or grammars) with very specific goals in design and implementation.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language can be one of a visual diagramming language, such as those created by the Generic Eclipse Modeling System, programmatic abstractions, such as the Eclipse Modeling Framework, or textual languages.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] For instance, the command line utility grep has a regular expression syntax which matches patterns in lines of text.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] The sed utility defines a syntax for matching and replacing regular expressions.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Often, these tiny languages can be used together inside a shell to perform more complex programming tasks.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] The line between domain-specific languages and scripting languages is somewhat blurred, but domain-specific languages often lack low-level functions for file system access, interprocess control, and other functions that characterize full-featured programming languages, scripting or otherwise.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Further blurring this line, many domain-specific languages have exposed APIs, and can be accessed from other programming languages without breaking the flow of execution or calling a separate process, and can thus operate as programming libraries.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Some domain-specific languages expand over time to include full-featured programming tools, which further complicates the question of whether a language is domain-specific or not.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] In model-driven engineering, many examples of domain-specific languages may be found like Object Constraint Language (OCL), a language for decorating models with assertions or Query/View/Transformation (QVT), a domain-specific transformation language.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] However, languages like Unified Modeling Language (UML) are typically general-purpose modeling languages.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] To summarize, an analogy is useful: a *very little language* is like a knife, which can be used in thousands of different ways, from cutting food to self-defense.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] A *domain-specific language* is like an electric drill: it is a powerful tool with a wide variety of uses, but a specific context, namely, making holes in things.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] A *general purpose language* is a complete workbench, with a variety of tools intended for performing a variety of tasks.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific languages should be used by programmers who, looking at their current workbench, realize they need a better drill and find that a given domain-specific language provides exactly that.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] DSLs implemented via an independent interpreter or compiler are termed *external domain specific languages*.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] A separate category termed *embedded (or internal) domain specific languages* are typically implemented within a host language as a library and tend to be limited to the syntax of the host language, though this depends on host language abilities.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Adopting a domain-specific language approach to software engineering involves both risks and opportunities.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] The well-designed domain-specific language manages to find the proper balance between these.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] GML is a domain-specific language used by GameMaker Studio designed to help novice programmers learn the fundamentals of coding more easily.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] It functions as a blend of several languages, including Delphi, C++, and BASIC.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Most GML functions, once compiled, call runtime functions written in the specific language of the target platform; consequently, their final implementation remains hidden from the user.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] The language's primary goal is to lower the barrier to entry for game development.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] The GameMaker runtime, which manages the main game loop and handles function implementation, allows a simple game to use only a few lines of code instead of thousands.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] ColdFusion's associated scripting language is another example of a domain-specific language for data-driven websites.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] The language is used to weave together languages and services such as Java, .NET, C++, SMS, email, email servers, http, ftp, exchange, directory services, and file systems for use in websites.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] The ColdFusion Markup Language (CFML) includes a set of tags that can be used in ColdFusion pages to interact with data sources, manipulate data, and display output.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] CFML tag syntax is similar to HTML element syntax.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Although the FilterMeister language reproduces a significant portion of the C language and function library, it contains only those features which can be used within the context of Photoshop plug-ins and adds a number of specific features only useful in this specific domain.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] The *Template* feature of MediaWiki is an embedded domain-specific language whose fundamental purpose is to support the creation of page templates and the transclusion (inclusion by reference) of MediaWiki pages into other MediaWiki pages.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] There has been much interest in domain-specific languages to improve the productivity and quality of software engineering.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific language could possibly provide a robust set of tools for efficient software engineering.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Such tools are beginning to make their way into the development of critical software systems.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] The Software Cost Reduction Toolkit is an example of this.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] A newer development is language-oriented programming, an integrated software engineering methodology based mainly on creating, optimizing, and using domain-specific languages.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Complementing language-oriented programming, and all other forms of domain-specific languages, are the class of compiler writing tools called metacompilers.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Such compiler is useful for generating parsers and code generators for domain-specific languages, and a metacompiler compiles a domain-specific metalanguage specifically designed for the domain of metaprogramming.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Besides parsing domain-specific languages, metacompilers are useful for generating a wide range of software engineering and analysis tools.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] The meta-compiler methodology is often found in program transformation systems.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Metacompilers that played a significant role in both computer science and the computer industry include META II, and its descendant TreeMeta.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Unreal and Unreal Tournament unveiled a language named UnrealScript.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] This allowed rapid development of modifications relative to the competitor Quake (using the Id Tech 2 engine).
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] The Id Tech engine used standard C code meaning C had to be learned and properly applied, while UnrealScript was optimized for ease of use and efficiency.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Similarly, more recent games have introduced their own specific languages for development.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] One more common example is Lua for scripting.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Various business rules engines have been developed for automating policy and business rules used in both government and private industry.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] ILOG, Oracle Policy Automation, DTRules, Drools and others provide support for DSLs aimed to support various problem domains.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] DTRules goes so far as to define an interface for the use of multiple DSLs within a rule set.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] The purpose of business rules engines is to define a representation of business logic in as human-readable fashion as possible.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] This allows both subject-matter experts and developers to work with and understand the same representation of the business logic.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Most rules engines provide both an approach to simplifying the control structures for business logic (for example, using declarative rules or decision tables) coupled with alternatives to programming syntax in favor of DSLs.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Statistical modelers have developed domain-specific languages such as R (an implementation of the S language), Bugs, Jags, and Stan.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] These languages provide a syntax for describing a Bayesian model and generate a method for solving it using simulation.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Generate object handling and services based on an Interface Description Language for a domain-specific language such as JavaScript for web applications, HTML for documentation, C++ for high-performance code, etc.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] This is done by cross-language frameworks such as Apache Thrift or Google Protocol Buffers.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Gherkin is a language designed to define test cases to check the behavior of software, without specifying how that behavior is implemented.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] It is meant to be read and used by non-technical users using a natural language syntax and a line-oriented design.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] The tests defined with Gherkin must then be implemented in a general programming language.
[src:starlark/domain-specific-language] Then, the steps in a Gherkin program acts as a syntax for method invocation accessible to non-developers.
